ding for the pair, producing market-wide DoS for that pool.","paths":["Point `nimbusReferralProgram` to a contract whose `recordFee()` always reverts; every `swap()` that reaches the referral branch reverts.","Use a token that blocks transfers to the configured referral address; `_safeTransfer(..., referralProgram, refFee)` then reverts and halts all swaps."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Factory can reinitialize an existing pair because initialization is not one-time","locations":["0xc0a6b8c534fad86df8fa1abb17084a70f86eddc1/Contract.sol:267","0xc0a6b8c534fad86df8fa1abb17084a70f86eddc1/Contract.sol:272","0xc0a6b8c534fad86df8fa1abb17084a70f86eddc1/Contract.sol:273","0xc0a6b8c534fad86df8fa1abb17084a70f86eddc1/Contract.sol:274","0xc0a6b8c534fad86df8fa1abb17084a70f86eddc1/Contract.sol:275"],"claim":"`initialize()` only checks `msg.sender == factory` and never verifies that `token0` and `token1` are unset. The factory can therefore overwrite the pair's asset addresses after deployment.","impact":"If the factory is misused or compromised, an active pool can be rebound to different tokens, permanently stranding the original reserves and breaking LP redemption assumptions.","paths":["Users deposit liquidity into a live pair.","The factory calls `initialize(maliciousTokenA, maliciousTokenB)` again, after which future `mint`, `burn`, and `swap` logic references the replacement tokens while the original assets remain trapped in the contract."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Any LP tokens held by the pair are permissionlessly redeemable, including misrouted protocol fees","locations":["0xc0a6b8c534fad86df8fa1abb17084a70f86eddc1/Contract.sol:296","0xc0a6b8c534fad86df8fa1abb17084a70f86eddc1/Contract.sol:307","0xc0a6b8c534fad86df8fa1abb17084a70f86eddc1/Contract.sol:340","0xc0a6b8c534fad86df8fa1abb17084a70f86eddc1/Contract.sol:346","0xc0a6b8c534fad86df8fa1abb17084a70f86eddc1/Contract.sol:353","0xc0a6b8c534fad86df8fa1abb17084a70f86eddc1/Contract.sol:354","0xc0a6b8c534fad86df8fa1abb17084a70f86eddc1/Contract.sol:355"],"claim":"`burn()` always redeems `balanceOf[address(this)]` and never authenticates who transferred or minted those LP tokens into the pair. As a result, any LP balance sitting on the pair contract can be burned by the first external caller and its underlying assets sent to an arbitrary recipient.","impact":"LP tokens accidentally sent to the pair can be stolen. If `feeTo` is ever misconfigured to the pair address, protocol fee LP minted by `_mintFee()` also become publicly claimable.","paths":["A user or integrator transfers LP tokens to the pair in one transaction and plans to call `burn()` later; an attacker frontruns or races with `burn(attacker)` and receives the underlying assets.","The factory sets `feeTo = address(pair)`, `_mintFee()` mints fee LP to the pair itself, and any caller later invokes `burn(attacker)` to redeem those protocol fees."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Flash loan attack via callback + skim allows stealing pool funds","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`swap()` and `skim()` share the same `lock` modifier, so `skim()` cannot be reentered from `NimbusCall`; the proposed exploit path is blocked."},{"title":"DOMAIN_SEPARATOR not updated on chain fork leading to signature reuse","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The code matches an older fixed-domain permit pattern, but the risk is fork-contingent and too speculative for a reportable issue in this audit."},{"title":"Swap callback allows arbitrary external calls enabling potential attack vectors","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is the standard flash-swap callback pattern; no concrete exploit survives the pair's reentrancy lock."},{"title":"Hardcoded magic number for infinite approval","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Readability issue only; not a security vulnerability."},{"title":"No check for zero-address in setFeeTo","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`setFeeTo` is not implemented in this contract, and a zero `feeTo` is the normal way to disable fees."},{"title":"Missing sync before K check","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The invariant check uses live token balances read immediately before validation, so a prior `sync()` is unnecessary."},{"title":"Anyone can steal tokens accidentally sent to the pair via skim","source_agents":["codex_1"],"reason":"`skim()` is an intentional Uniswap-style dust recovery mechanism that only transfers balances above recorded reserves; this is by design rather than a distinct vulnerability."}]}
